20149;instagram;2019-02-20 12:05:43;FALSE;what happens when all you feel is disappointment
i lived in these emotions for a very long time. i know what it feels like.
now i can look back across the road i walked. the road tattered with potholes and cracks of my own doing and i can see one thing.
i put myself there. with my decisions. my actions. my thoughts.
i was depressed because i stayed in the same thought process doing the same things over and over again until i made the decision to free myself and soar to new heights.
the question i have for you is this.
what decision are you not making today?
what thoughts are keeping you living in misery?
if you want to book a discovery call with me to address this you can below ‚ù§Ô∏è follow @jamesmalins

20151;instagram;2019-02-20 12:07:58;FALSE;i saw this post on facebook & found it the perfect opportunity to remind you that it‚Äôs okay to be mad about your past. it‚Äôs okay to transmit all the sadness and pain into anger
column2: because with anger can come justice.

column1: 20493;instagram;2019-02-20 18:20:09;FALSE;"i never thought i‚Äôd need this community. i have amazing best friends...i didn‚Äôt need any more. until i met them. until i saw that they were small town girls too with big time dreams. until they pushed me daily to be a better woman. until i saw that they have struggles too and share them fearlessly in hopes of helping other women. there‚Äôs a whole movement based around #metoo...these women all share their hearts daily in hopes that just one will say ‚Äúi relate to that‚Äù.

column1: 20497;instagram;2019-02-20 18:20:55;FALSE;"is it ok... if i'm vulnerable and transparent... if i confess the struggle is real... if i say the internal battle of the mind never ceases within me... that my ptsd gets the best of me at times and i want to runaway from my ownself... just to get away from the voices in my head that say........................ the images that always haunt and torment me on a daily basis..... the weeping... the sorrow... the self deprecating... the things i say about myself to myself i'd never even say to my worst enemy... wounds so deep that it will take a miracle to be healed... father
column2: the thorn in my side that i endure is has a hold of me and trying to consume me with its piercing jabs of past hurts... but god... i know you see me... i know you are hearing my cries... i know that in jesus' name there is deliverance... so i wait... and i wait.... the word is my defense sharper than any two edged sword... made of dust and dirt i know where i came from and where i was rescued out of... so i wait... this is a redemptive love story and for glory of the father that even the most deplorable things in life can be used to bring him praise... so in the waiting i will praise the  lord most high... because he is a good good father in good times and in bad... he is a good good father and i am very loved... ‚ù§

column1: founder and ceo williamson sintyl and board director @coveje (coco berthmann) are eager to enable all segments of society to actively join the fight against child-trafficking.
the new implemented plan of action to extend our program to survivors and victims of human trafficking within the usa will be essential part of ending modern-day slavery.

column2: we will be coming to your town. coco berthmann is an expert in human trafficking
column3: and survived 15 years of child trafficking herself. she speaks and lectures local leaders and law enforcement on the devastating reality of child trafficking and is determined to combine all forces to combat the insufferable torture of trafficking.

column2: ceo and founder of arise project of humanity survived the haitian earthquake and enables youth and young adults to break through the cycle of bad choices
column5: and unhealthy patterns through the mentoring program in haiti and now here in the usa!

column1: we want to come speak to you!
let us help you fight human trafficking by educating you and your community about the unbearable reality of modern-day slavery and what can be done within your community to stop it.

column1: 20723;instagram;2019-02-20 21:40:19;FALSE;"let‚Äôs talk about healing - and how we‚Äôre all allowed to heal.  none of us got to this point in life without some dings and scrapes.  just because other people have bigger bruises than ours does not mean that we should be ashamed of needing to heal from what happened to us.
it‚Äôs a frequent refrain in my conversations with women: ‚Äúsure
column2: he held me down and said nasty things to me
column3: but i got away.  it‚Äôs not like i was raped.  it could have been so much worse.  what do i have to complain about?‚Äù

column1: imagine you have two children - this week one of the children falls of the monkey bars (are those even still a thing?!?) and breaks their arm.  do you hug them and cradle them as they sob?  of course.

column2: the other child falls off the monkey bars and knocks out a tooth and gets a bump on the forehead.  do you tell that child not to cry because the other child is in the house with a cast on?  i would hope not.  you deal with the child that‚Äôs in front of you.  every child has different needs.  every child hurts in different ways.

column1: the same is true of adults.  we are allowed to feel sad and angry and all of the things.  telling ourselves that we shouldn‚Äôt feel those things is exactly the thing that blocks us from true healing.
thanks to @jessikneeland for telling your story so powerfully in this week‚Äôs podcast.

column1: 20727;instagram;2019-02-20 21:41:20;FALSE;"laura bates founded the everyday sexism project in 2012. it is a platform for sharing and recording stories of sexism
column3: to demonstrate that sexism does exist
column4: is faced by women daily and is a legitimate problem in need of discussion. ‚†Ä

column1: head here to share your story https://everydaysexism.com/‚†Ä ‚†Ä
bates most recently featured in the sunday times mag discussing misogyny in teenage boys. she argues that young men are being recruited online by alt-right/ anti-feminist  movements
column3: ‚Äúorchestrated to radicalise any and every boy online to hate women‚Äù. ‚†Ä

column1: bates has first-hand experience of its consequences when visiting schools to talk to teenagers
column2: hearing things like ‚Äúrape is a compliment
column3: really‚Äù and ‚Äúwhy are you coming to talk to us when far more men experience domestic abuse than women?‚Äù‚†Ä ‚†Ä

column1: her answer? bates believes the internet to be in its infancy. she argues that the negatives of being online (trolling
column3: targeted abuse etc) will be driven from the spaces as it matures

column1: 20736;instagram;2019-02-20 21:45:15;FALSE;"i have been hesitant to post newer poetry because i'm trying to save things for publication. the reason i am posting this now despite writing it a day or two ago is because i've recently watched a mini series by @illymation on youtube about abusive exes. this poem is about someone i broke up with over a year ago after dating him for about one and a half years before that. i met him when i was 15. he was 18
column2: soon to be 19 then. illy's animated series about her ""ex"" (her abuser) made me realize that this needs to be heard.

column1: the goal of this poem is for people to realize that abusers know what they're doing. they know what they're doing is wrong. maybe in some cases they start off not realizing it
column2: but they figure it out. they know what they are doing to you.

column1: and in case you haven't heard or need to hear it again
column2: it is not your fault. i'll say it a thousand times. it's not your fault. it wasn't my fault. it wasn't illy's fault.

column1: i can't link to all the resources here
column2: but check out @illymation on youtube to watch her story
column3: and she links to amazing resources there if you need help. you aren't helpless. you are strong.

column2: she names her abuser. i really like that
column3: but i leave names out of poetry to be more universal

column3: 2018 & it was my 26th birthday. as soon as i found out that the #womensmarch was on my birthday i knew that‚Äôs where i‚Äôd wanna spend it
column4: so me & tony shipped out to make some #pinkwaves & party with all these women standing up for our rights & screaming #fuckdonaldtrump for all of nyc to hear. it was magic.

column1: the rest of the weekend was also devoted to living our best life & i threw in some of that too
column2: but i wanted to post this because i didn‚Äôt get my birthday wish...

column1: my sign said ‚Äútoday is my 26th birthday & all i want this year is to stop getting sexually objectified.‚Äù (sorry i used to have some better pictures) & it was inspired by a year of working at a restaurant in which i was constantly sexually harassed & to be honest with you i myself even normalized it as the same shit you get in any kitchen
column2: but it‚Äôs all fun and games until it‚Äôs not.

column1: i had cooks complimenting me every day & that‚Äôs nice
column2: but then there‚Äôs what happens when you tell them no. one of the guys was a kitchen manager who then went on to sexually assault my friend & try to kiss her
column3: upon which she was grossed out & scared for her job. since the incident he remains a kitchen manger & she was told that because she didn‚Äôt want to get him in trouble her job was secured.

column1: what‚Äôs funny is my shift manager was also a predator. he was married with a baby but went on to message me & call me foxy as hell after seeing me in a bathing suit. i thought he was a cool guy so i humbly told him i‚Äôm no homewrecker &tried to laugh it off; my schedule was solid after that. it‚Äôs almost a joke to us sometimes
column2: the shit we put up with &all we can do is pray that we stay on their good side &have them by the balls a little bit. but the sad truth is that shit always goes wrong &women lose their jobs because they didn‚Äôt want to lose their dignity.

column1: even with guy friends it‚Äôs the sad truth. you think you‚Äôre homies but when you don‚Äôt want to give them the goods they switch up on you or think you‚Äôre playing hard to get. but tbh we just want to be treated as friends
